In article <404bdhINN5e9@garnet.bmr.gov.au> Peter Miller <pmiller@gneiss.bmr.gov.au> writes:

>
>
>     "Why aren't you considering freeware?"
>
> A8. There is poor documentation.
>
> Then why is DOS still here?   Why is UNIX still here?  I have used many
> pieces of commercial software with apalling documentation, and I have
> used freeware with excellent documentation.  Bookshelf-metres of
> documenation are a poor measure, too.  If the software does the job at
> the right price, what's the problem?
>

This is one point that hasn't been discussed much.  It's a major
concern, and the arguments above are basically irrelevant.

DOS and UNIX both depend highly on an aftermarket in documentation.  Most
freeware doesn't have that level of success, and thus can't be put
into the same class as DOS and UNIX.

It is true that there is commercial software that is crap (either code
or docs or both), and good freeware.  In the particular case of documentation,
my experience has been that the quality of the documentation in general is
poorer for freeware than commercial stuff.  [There are exceptions, and
I never let generalizations such as this control my decisions.]

The quantity of the documentation may not be a great measure, but it
does have some relevance in one respect.  A big problem with freeware
docs is that they're frequently targeted to expert users, and make
many assumptions about the users' backgrounds and experience.  Commercial
documentation is more likely to be targeted to average users (not always,
just more likely), while the sheer bulk of documentation may imply
different docs targeted  to different classes of users.

The final point in the above quote is just silly.  I've never seen a piece of
software that automatically unpacked and installed itself as soon as you put
the floppy in the drive (or finished the ftp to get the kit).  There's no such
thing as "software that does the job"; it's always "a person applying
software to do a job."  The quality of the software is irrelevant if no one
can figure out how to use or maintain it.

Case in point:  It's just taken me two full days to get the latest Perl
and Sybperl up and running (and I'll probably have to spend another couple
of hours to get it installed where it belongs).  It's great stuff (though
the Sybperl documentation is nonexistent), but that level of work just
to get an installation done is crap compared to the average (not the worst,
just the average) installation of comparable commercial tools.  And it's
the inadequacy of the documentation that is the largest contributor to
this deficiency.

