>1)  Freeware is written by people who aren't good enough to be
>programmers in industry; i.e. if they were good programmers with good
>products, they would be producing commercial software;
>
>2)  Commercial releases are more "trusted" to produce software and
>media free of trojan horses, viruses or other malicious code which can
>be uploaded to an unwitting ftp site.

I didn't mean to imply that the freeware concept is suspect. Only, as
you say, that distribution and support is suspect.

However, I've never run into anyone who felt the way you suggest in
points 1 and 2.

>Actually, it can be a complicated trade-off.  Getting 90% of the
>functionality for 10% of the price may be a fantastic trade-off for
>many people, but for a few it may be unacceptable.  If it is that
>final 10% which will give your business the competitive advantage, it
>is probably worth paying a lot of money for that final 10%.

Well, you're right about trade-offs. Of course, this implies that
businesses have enough information to make a good judgement. Promotion
is a double-edged sword in this regard. Commercial promotion (inc.
brochures, demos, specs, etc.) can help with decisions, but can also
trick you into buying poor products. Freeware promotion is largely
word-of-mouth, and probably doesn't have the same audience.

>If it's a good product and I feel I can trust the source of the
>software (the file itself, not the source code or its functionality),
>I'd certainly consider it for use on my systems, provided that we have
>the disk space for it and that using it doesn't violate any corporate
>policies.

This is a key point which relates back to credibility. Corporate
managers and lawyers are loathe to trust individuals or small
businesses supplying freeware or shareware. The idea is "if it sounds
too good to be true, it probably is".

>> They are pretty phenominal. Have you used them much? Beat GNU emacs
>> for a text editor and I will be very suprised.
>
>Not having used emacs (and no religious flame wars here either,
>please), I can't say.  But given the following it has, it must be a
>fantastic product.

Personally, I prefer emacs to vi (although I haven't used GNU emacs
specifically). I've also ported emacs to various platforms.
Nevertheless, there are many things I don't like about it. Obviously,
of course, the price it right!

>> I think that the profit from freeware comes in other ways. How hard
>>is it going to be for Larry Wall (creator of perl, among other
>>things) to ever find a job programming? If we all were laid off and
>>there were only 10 computer jobs left in the country he could have
>>his pick of them!

No offense to you or to Mr. Wall, but I wouldn't know him if he punched
me. For that matter, I know nothing about Perl either. This, I think,
relates back to my suggestions about promotion. What one person holds
up as godly, another may easily know nothing about. I suspect that many
(most?) corporate buyers spend their time with catalogs and
distributors, not surfing the internet for "deals".

I've often wondered how some of this truly amazing freeware/shareware
was developed. Frankly, I wouldn't have enough time or money to invest
that kind of effort with such a minimal chance of return. This is why I
stopped writing shareware several years ago.

>> As for support - beat comp.lang.perl with any commercial support in
>> the world! I really don't think you can!
>
>The net has certainly helped to throw the old rules out the window.
>Never before has there been a world-wide, almost instantaneous "grass
>roots" available to millions.

This is interesting. I wonder at what point we'll be able to
differentiate between "garage shop" Internet promotion and "corporate"
Internet promotion?

---

It seems that some have taken my earlier comments as put-downs of
freeware or shareware. Sorry, that wasn't my intent. I'm just tried to
explain some of the real and unreal reasons why it's not as popular as
you might hope. Decisions are very often made on an emotional, not
logical basis.

