I'd like to point out another reason that a lot of companies avoid using
freeware.  It came to me in a rush reading one of the responses to this
posting, which I agreed with on every point:

Software use decisions are almost always made by businessmen, not by
technicians.

Therefore, technical merit does not give the product credibility; and the
businessman (of course) finds it incredible that anybody would give away
something that is of real value.  There's no profit in that!  Obviously this is
the act of a lunatic, and so the software must be bad.

(sigh) We can point out these correct, realistic, convincing reasons until
we're blue in the face, and they won't sway the average decision-maker.

